# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] In statistics, an **autoregressive** (**AR**) **model** is a modelled representation of a type of random process.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] It can be used to describe time-varying processes from many natural and artificial sources.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The model specifies output variables that are dependent linearly on their own previous values on a stochastic basis.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The model is in the form of a stochastic difference equation (or recurrence relation) which should not be confused with a differential equation.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Another important extension is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, where the autoregressive coefficients are allowed to change over time to model evolving or non-stationary processes.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] TVAR models are widely applied in cases where the underlying dynamics of the system are not constant, such as in sensors time series modelling, climate science, economics and finance (as econometrics), signal processing, telecommunications, radar systems, and biological signals.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Unlike the moving-average (MA) model, the autoregressive model is not always stationary; non-stationarity can arise either due to the presence of a unit root or due to time-varying model parameters, as in time-varying autoregressive models.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Large language models are called autoregressive, but they are not a classical autoregressive model in this sense because they are not linear.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The notation $AR(p)$ indicates an autoregressive model of order *p*.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] where $\varphi _{1},\ldots ,\varphi _{p}$ are the *parameters* of the model, and $\varepsilon _{t}$ is white noise.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] An autoregressive model can thus be viewed as the output of an all-pole infinite impulse response filter whose input is white noise.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Some parameter constraints are necessary for the model to remain weak-sense stationary.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] For example, processes in the AR(1) model with $|\varphi _{1}|\geq 1$ are not stationary.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] More generally, for an AR(*p*) model to be weak-sense stationary, the roots of the polynomial $\Phi (z):=\textstyle 1-\sum _{i=1}^{p}\varphi _{i}z^{i}$ must lie outside the unit circle, i.e., each (complex) root $z_{i}$ must satisfy $|z_{i}|>1$ (see pages 89,92 ).
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] In an AR process, a one-time shock affects values of the evolving variable infinitely far into the future.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] A non-zero value for $\varepsilon _{t}$ at say time *t*=1 affects $X_{1}$ by the amount $\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{2}$ in terms of $X_{1}$ , this affects $X_{2}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{3}$ in terms of $X_{2}$ , this affects $X_{3}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}^{2}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Continuing this process shows that the effect of $\varepsilon _{1}$ never ends, although if the process is stationary then the effect diminishes toward zero in the limit.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Because each shock affects *X* values infinitely far into the future from when they occur, any given value *X**t* is affected by shocks occurring infinitely far into the past.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] When the polynomial division on the right side is carried out, the polynomial in the backshift operator applied to $\varepsilon _{t}$ has an infinite order—that is, an infinite number of lagged values of $\varepsilon _{t}$ appear on the right side of the equation.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] where *B* is the backshift operator, where $\varphi (\cdot )$ is the function defining the autoregression, and where $\varphi _{k}$ are the coefficients in the autoregression.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The formula is valid only if all the roots have multiplicity 1.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) process is a sum of decaying exponentials.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The simplest AR process is AR(0), which has no dependence between the terms.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Only the error/innovation/noise term contributes to the output of the process, so in the figure, AR(0) corresponds to white noise.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] For an AR(1) process with a positive $\varphi$ , only the previous term in the process and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi$ is close to 0, then the process still looks like white noise, but as $\varphi$ approaches 1, the output gets a larger contribution from the previous term relative to the noise.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] This results in a "smoothing" or integration of the output, similar to a low pass filter.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] For an AR(2) process, the previous two terms and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] If both $\varphi _{1}$ and $\varphi _{2}$ are positive, the output will resemble a low pass filter, with the high frequency part of the noise decreased.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi _{1}$ is positive while $\varphi _{2}$ is negative, then the process favors changes in sign between terms of the process.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] This can be linked to edge detection or detection of change in direction.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] An AR(1) process is given by: $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon _{t}\,$ where $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a white noise process with zero mean and constant variance $\sigma _{\varepsilon }^{2}$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] (Note: The subscript on $\varphi _{1}$ has been dropped.) The process is weak-sense stationary if $|\varphi |<1$ since it is obtained as the output of a stable filter whose input is white noise.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] where $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of $\varepsilon _{t}$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] and then by noticing that the quantity above is a stable fixed point of this relation.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] It can be seen that the autocovariance function decays with a decay time (also called time constant) of $\tau =1/(1-\varphi )$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The spectral density function is the Fourier transform of the autocovariance function.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] This expression is periodic due to the discrete nature of the $X_{j}$ , which is manifested as the cosine term in the denominator.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] where $\gamma =1/\tau$ is the angular frequency associated with the decay time $\tau$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] An alternative expression for $X_{t}$ can be derived by first substituting $\varphi X_{t-2}+\varepsilon _{t-1}$ for $X_{t-1}$ in the defining equation.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] It is seen that $X_{t}$ is white noise convolved with the $\varphi ^{k}$ kernel plus the constant mean.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] If the white noise $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a Gaussian process then $X_{t}$ is also a Gaussian process.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] In other cases, the central limit theorem indicates that $X_{t}$ will be approximately normally distributed when $\varphi$ is close to one.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] For $\varepsilon _{t}=0$ , the process $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}$ will be a geometric progression (*exponential* growth or decay).
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] In this case, the solution can be found analytically: $X_{t}=a\varphi ^{t}$ whereby a is an unknown constant (initial condition).
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The AR(1) model is the discrete-time analogy of the continuous Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] It is therefore sometimes useful to understand the properties of the AR(1) model cast in an equivalent form.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The partial autocorrelation of an AR(p) process equals zero at lags larger than *p*, so the appropriate maximum lag *p* is the one after which the partial autocorrelations are all zero.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] There are many ways to estimate the coefficients, such as the ordinary least squares procedure or method of moments (through Yule–Walker equations).
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] It is based on parameters $\varphi _{i}$ where *i* = 1, ..., *p*.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] There is a direct correspondence between these parameters and the covariance function of the process, and this correspondence can be inverted to determine the parameters from the autocorrelation function (which is itself obtained from the covariances).
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] This is done using the Yule–Walker equations.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The Yule–Walker equations, named for Udny Yule and Gilbert Walker, are the following set of equations.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Here $\gamma _{m}$ is the autocovariance function of Xt, $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of the input noise process, and $\delta _{m,0}$ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] An alternative formulation is in terms of the autocorrelation function.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The AR parameters are determined by the first *p*+1 elements $\rho (\tau )$ of the autocorrelation function.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The above equations (the Yule–Walker equations) provide several routes to estimating the parameters of an AR(*p*) model, by replacing the theoretical covariances with estimated values.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] but the reasoning behind this applies to the use of any set of estimated AR parameters.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Compared to the estimation scheme using only the forward prediction equations, different estimates of the autocovariances are produced, and the estimates have different stability properties.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Other possible approaches to estimation include maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Substantial differences in the results of these approaches can occur if the observed series is short, or if the process is close to non-stationarity.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The terms involving square roots are all real in the case of complex poles since they exist only when $\varphi _{2}<0$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The process is non-stationary when the poles are on or outside the unit circle, or equivalently when the characteristic roots are on or inside the unit circle.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The process is stable when the poles are strictly within the unit circle (roots strictly outside the unit circle), or equivalently when the coefficients are in the triangle $-1\leq \varphi _{2}\leq 1-|\varphi _{1}|$ .
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The impulse response of a system is the change in an evolving variable in response to a change in the value of a shock term *k* periods earlier, as a function of *k*.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Since the AR model is a special case of the vector autoregressive model, the computation of the impulse response in vector autoregression#impulse response applies here.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] have been estimated, the autoregression can be used to forecast an arbitrary number of periods into the future.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] The output of the autoregressive equation is the forecast for the first unobserved period.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Then for future periods the same procedure is used, each time using one more forecast value on the right side of the predictive equation until, after *p* predictions, all *p* right-side values are predicted values from preceding steps.
[src:state-space-models/autoregressive-model] Each of the last three can be quantified and combined to give a confidence interval for the *n*-step-ahead predictions; the confidence interval will become wider as *n* increases because of the use of an increasing number of estimated values for the right-side variables.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In probability theory, a **hidden Markov model** (**HMM**) is a Markov model in which the observations are dependent on a latent (or *hidden*) Markov process (referred to as X ).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] An HMM requires that there be an observable process Y whose outcomes depend on the outcomes of X in a known way.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Since X cannot be observed directly, the goal is to learn about state of X by observing Y .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Estimation of the parameters in an HMM can be performed using maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] For linear chain HMMs, the Baum–Welch algorithm can be used to estimate parameters.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Let $X_{n}$ and $Y_{n}$ be discrete-time stochastic processes and $n\geq 1$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Let $X_{t}$ and $Y_{t}$ be continuous-time stochastic processes.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In its discrete form, a hidden Markov process can be visualized as a generalization of the urn problem with replacement (where each item from the urn is returned to the original urn before the next step).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In a room that is not visible to an observer there is a genie.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The room contains urns X1, X2, X3, ... each of which contains a known mix of balls, with each ball having a unique label y1, y2, y3, ... .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The genie chooses an urn in that room and randomly draws a ball from that urn.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] It then puts the ball onto a conveyor belt, where the observer can observe the sequence of the balls but not the sequence of urns from which they were drawn.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Therefore, this is called a Markov process.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] It can be described by the upper part of Figure 1.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The Markov process cannot be observed, only the sequence of labeled balls, thus this arrangement is called a *hidden Markov process*.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This is illustrated by the lower part of the diagram shown in Figure 1, where one can see that balls y1, y2, y3, y4 can be drawn at each state.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Even if the observer knows the composition of the urns and has just observed a sequence of three balls, *e.g.* y1, y2 and y3 on the conveyor belt, the observer still cannot be *sure* which urn (*i.e.*, at which state) the genie has drawn the third ball from.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] However, the observer can work out other information, such as the likelihood that the third ball came from each of the urns.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Consider two friends, Alice and Bob, who live far apart from each other and who talk together daily over the telephone about what they did that day.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Bob is only interested in three activities: walking in the park, shopping, and cleaning his apartment.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The choice of what to do is determined exclusively by the weather on a given day.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Alice has no definite information about the weather, but she knows general trends.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Based on what Bob tells her he did each day, Alice tries to guess what the weather must have been like.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Alice believes that the weather operates as a discrete Markov chain.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] There are two states, "Rainy" and "Sunny", but she cannot observe them directly, that is, they are *hidden* from her.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] On each day, there is a certain chance that Bob will perform one of the following activities, depending on the weather: "walk", "shop", or "clean".
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Since Bob tells Alice about his activities, those are the *observations*.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The entire system is that of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Alice knows the general weather trends in the area, and what Bob likes to do on average.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In other words, the parameters of the HMM are known.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In this piece of code, `start_probability` represents Alice's belief about which state the HMM is in when Bob first calls her (all she knows is that it tends to be rainy on average).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The particular probability distribution used here is not the equilibrium one, which is (given the transition probabilities) approximately `{'Rainy': 0.57, 'Sunny': 0.43}`.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The `transition_probability` represents the change of the weather in the underlying Markov chain.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In this example, there is only a 30% chance that tomorrow will be sunny if today is rainy.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The `emission_probability` represents how likely Bob is to perform a certain activity on each day.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] If it is rainy, there is a 50% chance that he is cleaning his apartment; if it is sunny, there is a 60% chance that he is outside for a walk.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The diagram below shows the general architecture of an instantiated HMM.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Each oval shape represents a random variable that can adopt any of a number of values.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The random variable *x*(*t*) is the hidden state at time t (with the model from the above diagram, *x*(*t*) ∈ {‍*x*1, *x*2, *x*3‍}).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The arrows in the diagram (often called a trellis diagram) denote conditional dependencies.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] From the diagram, it is clear that the conditional probability distribution of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) at time t, given the values of the hidden variable x at all times, depends *only* on the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t* − 1); the values at time *t* − 2 and before have no influence.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Similarly, the value of the observed variable *y*(*t*) depends on only the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) (both at time t).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In the standard type of hidden Markov model considered here, the state space of the hidden variables is discrete, while the observations themselves can either be discrete (typically generated from a categorical distribution) or continuous (typically from a Gaussian distribution).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The parameters of a hidden Markov model are of two types, *transition probabilities* and *emission probabilities* (also known as *output probabilities*).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The transition probabilities control the way the hidden state at time t is chosen given the hidden state at time *t* − 1.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The hidden state space is assumed to consist of one of N possible values, modelled as a categorical distribution.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The set of transition probabilities for transitions from any given state must sum to 1.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Thus, the *N* × *N* matrix of transition probabilities is a Markov matrix.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Because any transition probability can be determined once the others are known, there are a total of *N*(*N* − 1) transition parameters.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In addition, for each of the N possible states, there is a set of emission probabilities governing the distribution of the observed variable at a particular time given the state of the hidden variable at that time.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The size of this set depends on the nature of the observed variable.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] For example, if the observed variable is discrete with M possible values, governed by a categorical distribution, there will be *M* − 1 separate parameters, for a total of *N*(*M* − 1) emission parameters over all hidden states.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Several inference problems are associated with hidden Markov models, as outlined below.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The task is to compute in a best way, given the parameters of the model, the probability of a particular output sequence.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Applying the principle of dynamic programming, this problem, too, can be handled efficiently using the forward algorithm.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] A number of related tasks ask about the probability of one or more of the latent variables, given the model's parameters and a sequence of observations $y(1),\dots ,y(t)$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The task is to compute, given the model's parameters and a sequence of observations, the distribution over hidden states of the last latent variable at the end of the sequence, i.e. to compute $P(x(t)\mid y(1),\dots ,y(t))$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This task is used when the sequence of latent variables is thought of as the underlying states that a process moves through at a sequence of points in time, with corresponding observations at each point.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Then, it is natural to ask about the state of the process at the end.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This problem can be handled efficiently using the forward algorithm.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] An example is when the algorithm is applied to a Hidden Markov Network to determine $\mathrm {P} {\big (}h_{t}\mid v_{1:t}{\big )}$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This is similar to filtering but asks about the distribution of a latent variable somewhere in the middle of a sequence, i.e. to compute $P(x(k)\mid y(1),\dots ,y(t))$ for some $k<t$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] From the perspective described above, this can be thought of as the probability distribution over hidden states for a point in time *k* in the past, relative to time *t*.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The forward-backward algorithm is a good method for computing the smoothed values for all hidden state variables.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The task, unlike the previous two, asks about the joint probability of the *entire* sequence of hidden states that generated a particular sequence of observations (see illustration on the right).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This task is generally applicable when HMM's are applied to different sorts of problems from those for which the tasks of filtering and smoothing are applicable.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] An example is part-of-speech tagging, where the hidden states represent the underlying parts of speech corresponding to an observed sequence of words.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In this case, what is of interest is the entire sequence of parts of speech, rather than simply the part of speech for a single word, as filtering or smoothing would compute.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This task requires finding a maximum over all possible state sequences, and can be solved efficiently by the Viterbi algorithm.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] For some of the above problems, it may also be interesting to ask about statistical significance.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] What is the probability that a sequence drawn from some null distribution will have an HMM probability (in the case of the forward algorithm) or a maximum state sequence probability (in the case of the Viterbi algorithm) at least as large as that of a particular output sequence?
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] When an HMM is used to evaluate the relevance of a hypothesis for a particular output sequence, the statistical significance indicates the false positive rate associated with failing to reject the hypothesis for the output sequence.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The parameter learning task in HMMs is to find, given an output sequence or a set of such sequences, the best set of state transition and emission probabilities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The task is usually to derive the maximum likelihood estimate of the parameters of the HMM given the set of output sequences.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] No tractable algorithm is known for solving this problem exactly, but a local maximum likelihood can be derived efficiently using the Baum–Welch algorithm or the Baldi–Chauvin algorithm.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The Baum–Welch algorithm is a special case of the expectation-maximization algorithm.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] If the HMMs are used for time series prediction, more sophisticated Bayesian inference methods, like Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampling are proven to be favorable over finding a single maximum likelihood model both in terms of accuracy and stability.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Since MCMC imposes significant computational burden, in cases where computational scalability is also of interest, one may alternatively resort to variational approximations to Bayesian inference, e.g.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Indeed, approximate variational inference offers computational efficiency comparable to expectation-maximization, while yielding an accuracy profile only slightly inferior to exact MCMC-type Bayesian inference.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] HMMs can be applied in many fields where the goal is to recover a data sequence that is not immediately observable (but other data that depend on the sequence are).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Hidden Markov models were described in a series of statistical papers by Leonard E.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Baum and other authors in the second half of the 1960s.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] One of the first applications of HMMs was speech recognition, starting in the mid-1970s.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] From the linguistics point of view, hidden Markov models are equivalent to stochastic regular grammar.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In the second half of the 1980s, HMMs began to be applied to the analysis of biological sequences, in particular DNA.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Since then, they have become ubiquitous in the field of bioinformatics.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In the hidden Markov models considered above, the state space of the hidden variables is discrete, while the observations themselves can either be discrete (typically generated from a categorical distribution) or continuous (typically from a Gaussian distribution).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Hidden Markov models can also be generalized to allow continuous state spaces.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Examples of such models are those where the Markov process over hidden variables is a linear dynamical system, with a linear relationship among related variables and where all hidden and observed variables follow a Gaussian distribution.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Nowadays, inference in hidden Markov models is performed in nonparametric settings, where the dependency structure enables identifiability of the model and the learnability limits are still under exploration.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The above algorithms implicitly assume a uniform prior distribution over the transition probabilities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] However, it is also possible to create hidden Markov models with other types of prior distributions.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] An obvious candidate, given the categorical distribution of the transition probabilities, is the Dirichlet distribution, which is the conjugate prior distribution of the categorical distribution.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Typically, a symmetric Dirichlet distribution is chosen, reflecting ignorance about which states are inherently more likely than others.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The single parameter of this distribution (termed the *concentration parameter*) controls the relative density or sparseness of the resulting transition matrix.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] A choice of 1 yields a uniform distribution.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Values greater than 1 produce a dense matrix, in which the transition probabilities between pairs of states are likely to be nearly equal.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Values less than 1 result in a sparse matrix in which, for each given source state, only a small number of destination states have non-negligible transition probabilities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] It is also possible to use a two-level prior Dirichlet distribution, in which one Dirichlet distribution (the upper distribution) governs the parameters of another Dirichlet distribution (the lower distribution), which in turn governs the transition probabilities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The upper distribution governs the overall distribution of states, determining how likely each state is to occur; its concentration parameter determines the density or sparseness of states.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The parameters of models of this sort, with non-uniform prior distributions, can be learned using Gibbs sampling or extended versions of the expectation-maximization algorithm.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] An extension of the previously described hidden Markov models with Dirichlet priors uses a Dirichlet process in place of a Dirichlet distribution.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This type of model allows for an unknown and potentially infinite number of states.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] It is common to use a two-level Dirichlet process, similar to the previously described model with two levels of Dirichlet distributions.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Such a model is called a *hierarchical Dirichlet process hidden Markov model*, or *HDP-HMM* for short.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] It was originally described under the name "Infinite Hidden Markov Model" and was further formalized in "Hierarchical Dirichlet Processes".
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] A different type of extension uses a discriminative model in place of the generative model of standard HMMs.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This type of model directly models the conditional distribution of the hidden states given the observations, rather than modeling the joint distribution.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] An example of this model is the so-called *maximum entropy Markov model* (MEMM), which models the conditional distribution of the states using logistic regression (also known as a "maximum entropy model").
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The advantage of this type of model is that arbitrary features (i.e. functions) of the observations can be modeled, allowing domain-specific knowledge of the problem at hand to be injected into the model.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Furthermore, there is no need for these features to be statistically independent of each other, as would be the case if such features were used in a generative model.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Finally, arbitrary features over pairs of adjacent hidden states can be used rather than simple transition probabilities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantages of such models are: (1) The types of prior distributions that can be placed on hidden states are severely limited; (2) It is not possible to predict the probability of seeing an arbitrary observation.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This second limitation is often not an issue in practice, since many common usages of HMM's do not require such predictive probabilities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] A variant of the previously described discriminative model is the linear-chain conditional random field.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This uses an undirected graphical model (aka Markov random field) rather than the directed graphical models of MEMM's and similar models.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The advantage of this type of model is that it does not suffer from the so-called *label bias* problem of MEMM's, and thus may make more accurate predictions.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantage is that training can be slower than for MEMM's.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Yet another variant is the *factorial hidden Markov model*, which allows for a single observation to be conditioned on the corresponding hidden variables of a set of K independent Markov chains, rather than a single Markov chain.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] It is equivalent to a single HMM, with $N^{K}$ states (assuming there are N states for each chain), and therefore, learning in such a model is difficult: for a sequence of length T , a straightforward Viterbi algorithm has complexity $O(N^{2K}\,T)$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] To find an exact solution, a junction tree algorithm could be used, but it results in an $O(N^{K+1}\,K\,T)$ complexity.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In practice, approximate techniques, such as variational approaches, could be used.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantage of such models is that dynamic-programming algorithms for training them have an $O(N^{K}\,T)$ running time, for K adjacent states and T total observations (i.e. a length- T Markov chain).
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This extension has been widely used in bioinformatics, in the modeling of DNA sequences.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Another recent extension is the *triplet Markov model*, in which an auxiliary underlying process is added to model some data specificities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Many variants of this model have been proposed.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] One should also mention the interesting link that has been established between the *theory of evidence* and the *triplet Markov models* and which allows to fuse data in Markovian context and to model nonstationary data.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Finally, a different rationale towards addressing the problem of modeling nonstationary data by means of hidden Markov models was suggested in 2012.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] It consists in employing a small recurrent neural network (RNN), specifically a reservoir network, to capture the evolution of the temporal dynamics in the observed data.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This information, encoded in the form of a high-dimensional vector, is used as a conditioning variable of the HMM state transition probabilities.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Under such a setup, eventually is obtained a nonstationary HMM, the transition probabilities of which evolve over time in a manner that is inferred from the data, in contrast to some unrealistic ad-hoc model of temporal evolution.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] In 2023, two innovative algorithms were introduced for the Hidden Markov Model.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] These algorithms enable the computation of the posterior distribution of the HMM without the necessity of explicitly modeling the joint distribution, utilizing only the conditional distributions.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Unlike traditional methods such as the Forward-Backward and Viterbi algorithms, which require knowledge of the joint law of the HMM and can be computationally intensive to learn, the Discriminative Forward-Backward and Discriminative Viterbi algorithms circumvent the need for the observation's law.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] This breakthrough allows the HMM to be applied as a discriminative model, offering a more efficient and versatile approach to leveraging Hidden Markov Models in various applications.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The model suitable in the context of longitudinal data is named latent Markov model.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The basic version of this model has been extended to include individual covariates, random effects and to model more complex data structures such as multilevel data.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Given a Markov transition matrix and an invariant distribution on the states, a probability measure can be imposed on the set of subshifts.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] For example, consider the Markov chain given on the right on the states $A,B_{1},B_{2}$ , with invariant distribution $\pi =(2/7,4/7,1/7)$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] By ignoring the distinction between $B_{1},B_{2}$ , this space of subshifts is projected on $A,B_{1},B_{2}$ into another space of subshifts on $A,B$ , and this projection also projects the probability measure down to a probability measure on the subshifts on $A,B$ .
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] The curious thing is that the probability measure on the subshifts on $A,B$ is not created by a Markov chain on $A,B$ , not even multiple orders.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Intuitively, this is because if one observes a long sequence of $B^{n}$ , then one would become increasingly sure that the $\Pr(A\mid B^{n})\to {\frac {2}{3}}$ , meaning that the observable part of the system can be affected by something infinitely in the past.
[src:state-space-models/hidden-markov-model] Conversely, there exists a space of subshifts on 6 symbols, projected to subshifts on 2 symbols, such that any Markov measure on the smaller subshift has a preimage measure that is not Markov of any order (example 2.6).
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] A **latent variable model** is a statistical model that relates a set of observable variables (also called *manifest variables* or *indicators*) to a set of latent variables.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] Latent variable models are applied across a wide range of fields such as biology, computer science, and social science.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] It is assumed that the responses on the indicators or manifest variables are the result of an individual's position on the latent variable(s), and that the manifest variables have nothing in common after controlling for the latent variable (local independence).
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] The Rasch model represents the simplest form of item response theory.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] Mixture models are central to latent profile analysis.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] In factor analysis and latent trait analysis the latent variables are treated as continuous normally distributed variables, and in latent profile analysis and latent class analysis as from a multinomial distribution.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] The manifest variables in factor analysis and latent profile analysis are continuous and in most cases, their conditional distribution given the latent variables is assumed to be normal.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] In latent trait analysis and latent class analysis, the manifest variables are discrete.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] These variables could be dichotomous, ordinal or nominal variables.
[src:state-space-models/latent-variable-model] Their conditional distributions are assumed to be binomial or multinomial.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] The process relies heavily upon mathematical concepts and models that are theorized within a study of prior and posterior probabilities known as Bayesian statistics.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] A Bayes filter is an algorithm used in computer science for calculating the probabilities of multiple beliefs to allow a robot to infer its position and orientation.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] Essentially, Bayes filters allow robots to continuously update their most likely position within a coordinate system, based on the most recently acquired sensor data.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] It consists of two parts: prediction and innovation.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] If the variables are normally distributed and the transitions are linear, the Bayes filter becomes equal to the Kalman filter.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] In a simple example, a robot moving throughout a grid may have several different sensors that provide it with information about its surroundings.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] The robot may begin with certainty that it is at position (0,0).
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] The measurements z are the manifestations of a hidden Markov model (HMM), which means the true state x is assumed to be an unobserved Markov process.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] The following picture presents a Bayesian network of a HMM.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] Because of the Markov assumption, the probability of the current true state given the immediately previous one is conditionally independent of the other earlier states.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] Similarly, the measurement at the *k*-th timestep is dependent only upon the current state, so is conditionally independent of all other states given the current state.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] However, when using the Kalman filter to estimate the state **x**, the probability distribution of interest is associated with the current states conditioned on the measurements up to the current timestep.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] This leads to the *predict* and *update* steps of the Kalman filter written probabilistically.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] The probability distribution of update is proportional to the product of the measurement likelihood and the predicted state.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] is constant relative to x , so we can always substitute it for a coefficient $\alpha$ , which can usually be ignored in practice.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] The numerator can be calculated and then simply normalized, since its integral must be unity.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] Sequential Bayesian filtering is the extension of the Bayesian estimation for the case when the observed value changes in time.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] It is a method to estimate the real value of an observed variable that evolves in time.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] value given past and current observations.
[src:state-space-models/recursive-bayesian-estimation] The notion of Sequential Bayesian filtering is extensively used in control and robotics.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] In statistics and image processing, to **smooth** a data set is to create an approximating function that attempts to capture important patterns in the data, while leaving out noise or other fine-scale structures/rapid phenomena.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] In smoothing, the data points of a signal are modified so individual points higher than the adjacent points (presumably because of noise) are reduced, and points that are lower than the adjacent points are increased, leading to a smoother signal.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] Provide analyses that are both flexible and robust.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] Many different algorithms are used in smoothing, most commonly binning, kernels, and local weighted regression.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] In the case that the smoothed values can be written as a linear transformation of the observed values, the smoothing operation is known as a **linear smoother**; the matrix representing the transformation is known as a **smoother matrix** or hat matrix.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] The operation of applying such a matrix transformation is called convolution.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] Thus the matrix is also called convolution matrix or a convolution kernel.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] In the case of simple series of data points (rather than a multi-dimensional image), the convolution kernel is a one-dimensional vector.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] One of the most common algorithms is the "moving average", often used to try to capture important trends in repeated statistical surveys.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] In image processing and computer vision, smoothing ideas are used in scale space representations.
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] The simplest smoothing algorithm is the "rectangular" or "unweighted sliding-average smooth".
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] This method replaces each point in the signal with the average of "m" adjacent points, where "m" is a positive integer called the "smooth width".
[src:state-space-models/smoothing] The *triangular smooth* is like the *rectangular smooth* except that it implements a weighted smoothing function.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] In control engineering and system identification, a **state-space representation** is a mathematical model of a physical system that uses state variables to track how inputs shape system behavior over time through first-order differential equations or difference equations.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] These state variables change based on their current values and inputs, while outputs depend on the states and sometimes the inputs too.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The **state space** (also called **time-domain approach** and equivalent to phase space in certain dynamical systems) is a geometric space where the axes are these state variables, and the system’s state is represented by a state vector.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] For linear, time-invariant, and finite-dimensional systems, the equations can be written in matrix form, offering a compact alternative to the frequency domain’s Laplace transforms for multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Unlike the frequency domain approach, it works for systems beyond just linear ones with zero initial conditions.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This approach turns systems theory into an algebraic framework, making it possible to use Kronecker structures for efficient analysis.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] State-space models are applied in fields such as economics, statistics, computer science, electrical engineering, and neuroscience.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] In econometrics, for example, state-space models can be used to decompose a time series into trend and cycle, compose individual indicators into a composite index, identify turning points of the business cycle, and estimate GDP using latent and unobserved time series.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Many applications rely on the Kalman Filter or a state observer to produce estimates of the current unknown state variables using their previous observations.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The internal state variables are the smallest possible subset of system variables that can represent the entire state of the system at any given time.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The minimum number of state variables required to represent a given system, n , is usually equal to the order of the system's defining differential equation, but not necessarily.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] If the system is represented in transfer function form, the minimum number of state variables is equal to the order of the transfer function's denominator after it has been reduced to a proper fraction.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] It is important to understand that converting a state-space realization to a transfer function form may lose some internal information about the system, and may provide a description of a system which is stable, when the state-space realization is unstable at certain points.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] In electric circuits, the number of state variables is often, though not always, the same as the number of energy storage elements in the circuit such as capacitors and inductors.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The state variables defined must be linearly independent, i.e., no state variable can be written as a linear combination of the other state variables.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] In this general formulation, all matrices are allowed to be time-variant (i.e. their elements can depend on time); however, in the common LTI case, matrices will be time invariant.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The time variable t can be continuous (e.g. $t\in \mathbb {R}$ ) or discrete (e.g. $t\in \mathbb {Z}$ ).
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] In the latter case, the time variable k is usually used instead of t .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Hybrid systems allow for time domains that have both continuous and discrete parts.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Stability and natural response characteristics of a continuous-time LTI system (i.e., linear with matrices that are constant with respect to time) can be studied from the eigenvalues of the matrix $\mathbf {A}$ .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The stability of a time-invariant state-space model can be determined by looking at the system's transfer function in factored form.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] These poles can be used to analyze whether the system is asymptotically stable or marginally stable.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] An alternative approach to determining stability, which does not involve calculating eigenvalues, is to analyze the system's Lyapunov stability.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The zeros found in the numerator of $\mathbf {G} (s)$ can similarly be used to determine whether the system is minimum phase.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The system may still be **input–output stable** (see BIBO stable) even though it is not internally stable.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This may be the case if unstable poles are canceled out by zeros (i.e., if those singularities in the transfer function are removable).
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The state controllability condition implies that it is possible – by admissible inputs – to steer the states from any initial value to any final value within some finite time window.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Observability is a measure for how well internal states of a system can be inferred by knowledge of its external outputs.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Assuming zero initial conditions $\mathbf {x} (0)=\mathbf {0}$ and a single-input single-output (SISO) system, the transfer function is defined as the ratio of output and input $G(s)=Y(s)/U(s)$ .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] For a multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) system, however, this ratio is not defined.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Consequently, $\mathbf {G} (s)$ is a matrix with the dimension $q\times p$ which contains transfer functions for each input output combination.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Due to the simplicity of this matrix notation, the state-space representation is commonly used for multiple-input, multiple-output systems.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The Rosenbrock system matrix provides a bridge between the state-space representation and its transfer function.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Given a transfer function, expand it to reveal all coefficients in both the numerator and denominator.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This state-space realization is called **controllable canonical form** because the resulting model is guaranteed to be controllable (i.e., because the control enters a chain of integrators, it has the ability to move every state).
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This state-space realization is called **observable canonical form** because the resulting model is guaranteed to be observable (i.e., because the output exits from a chain of integrators, every state has an effect on the output).
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Transfer functions which are only proper (and not strictly proper) can also be realised quite easily.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The strictly proper transfer function can then be transformed into a canonical state-space realization using techniques shown above.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The state-space realization of the constant is trivially $\mathbf {y} (t)=\mathbf {G} (\infty )\mathbf {u} (t)$ .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Together we then get a state-space realization with matrices *A*, *B* and *C* determined by the strictly proper part, and matrix *D* determined by the constant.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This is due to the $\mathbf {G} (\infty )$ constant in the transfer function.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] A common method for feedback is to multiply the output by a matrix *K* and setting this as the input to the system: $\mathbf {u} (t)=K\mathbf {y} (t)$ .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Since the values of *K* are unrestricted the values can easily be negated for negative feedback.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The presence of a negative sign (the common notation) is merely a notational one and its absence has no impact on the end results.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The advantage of this is that the eigenvalues of *A* can be controlled by setting *K* appropriately through eigendecomposition of $\left(A+BK\left(I-DK\right)^{-1}C\right)$ .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This assumes that the closed-loop system is controllable or that the unstable eigenvalues of *A* can be made stable through appropriate choice of *K*.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] For a strictly proper system *D* equals zero.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Another fairly common situation is when all states are outputs, i.e.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] *y* = *x*, which yields *C* = *I*, the identity matrix.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This reduces the necessary eigendecomposition to just $A+BK$ .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] In addition to feedback, an input, $r(t)$ , can be added such that $\mathbf {u} (t)=-K\mathbf {y} (t)+\mathbf {r} (t)$ .
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] A classical linear system is that of one-dimensional movement of an object (e.g., a cart).
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] This means, that if initial state of the system is known ( $y(t)$ , ${\dot {y}}(t)$ , ${\ddot {y}}(t)$ ), and if the b and m are constants, then there is a force u that could move the cart into any other position in the system.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] Therefore, this system is both controllable and observable.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The more general form of a state-space model can be written as two functions.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The first is the state equation and the latter is the output equation.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] If the function $f(\cdot ,\cdot ,\cdot )$ is a linear combination of states and inputs then the equations can be written in matrix notation like above.
[src:state-space-models/state-space-representation] The $u(t)$ argument to the functions can be dropped if the system is unforced (i.e., it has no inputs).
